1. Project Goal:
   This project predicts house prices based on multiple property features including
   area, number of bedrooms, bathrooms, and amenities. Built as a practical
   application of linear regression on real estate data.

2. Dataset:
   Kaggle Housing dataset containing 545 properties with 12 input features and
   one target variable (price). Features include both numerical values like area
   and bedrooms, and categorical values like mainroad access, furnishing status,
   and air conditioning.

3. EDA Findings:
   No missing values were found in this dataset. Statistical analysis revealed
   mean price (4.76M) is greater than median (4.34M), indicating right skew,
   a small number of very expensive properties are pulling the average upward.
   This suggested the presence of high-value outliers which were later confirmed
   through RMSE analysis.

4. Methodology:

   a. EDA: Explored dataset structure, checked for missing values, and
   analyzed statistical distributions of all features.

   b. Feature Relationships: Investigated relationships through scatter plots,
   boxplots for categorical features, and a correlation matrix to identify
   which features impact price most strongly.

   c. Missing Data: No missing values were found so no imputation was required.

   d. Train Test Split: Dataset split into 70% training and 30% test set before
   any preprocessing to prevent data leakage.

   e. Feature Engineering: Created a new feature area_parking by combining area
   and parking columns, which showed strong correlation with price. This was
   done after splitting to avoid data leakage.

   f. Model Building: Trained a Linear Regression model using 3-fold cross
   validation to evaluate reliability before final training.

   g. Visualization: Three plots were used to evaluate model performance —
   actual vs predicted values showing linear relationship, residual plot
   confirming homoscedasticity, and coefficient plot identifying most
   important features.

   h. Evaluation: Model evaluated using MAE, MSE, RMSE and R² score.

5. Results:
   R² = 0.64 means the model explains 64% of house price variation through
   input features. The remaining 36% is influenced by factors not captured
   in the dataset such as location quality, neighborhood, and market conditions.

6. Key Observation:
   RMSE (1,238,970) is significantly higher than MAE (925,543). This gap
   indicates outlier properties are disproportionately inflating the error —
   a sign that outlier removal could meaningfully improve model performance.
   This was identified as the primary limitation of the current model.

7. Future Improvements:
   Primary improvement is outlier removal using IQR method before model
   training. Additional improvements include trying polynomial regression
   to capture non-linear relationships, adding interaction features beyond
   area_parking, and exploring more advanced models like Random Forest
   for comparison.
